<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="u6-constraints-svd" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Constraints and SVD</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Constraints and matrix factorizations both ask for special directions. Lagrange multipliers find directions compatible with constraints. SVD finds the input directions where a matrix map stretches, weakens, or forgets information.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Big question.</em> What directions matter most in a constrained problem or matrix map?
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Learning outcomes.</em> By the end of this unit, students should be able to:
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Core outcomes.</em>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><p><em>U6-LO1.</em> Find absolute extrema on closed bounded regions by comparing interior and boundary candidates.</p></li>
      <li><p><em>U6-LO2.</em> Set up and solve one-constraint Lagrange-multiplier problems, and interpret the condition <m>\nabla f=\lambda\nabla g</m> as parallel gradients.</p></li>
      <li><p><em>U6-LO3.</em> Compute singular values and singular vectors in small examples and connect them to eigenvectors of <m>A^TA</m>.</p></li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <em>U6-LO4.</em> Construct and interpret an SVD
          <me>A=U\Sigma V^T,</me>
          including the roles of <m>U</m>, <m>\Sigma</m>, and <m>V^T</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li><p><em>U6-LO5.</em> Use SVD to identify rank and orthonormal bases for the four fundamental subspaces.</p></li>
      <li><p><em>U6-LO6.</em> Interpret singular values as stretch factors and as transmitted, weak, or forgotten directions.</p></li>
      <li><p><em>U6-LO7.</em> Use truncated SVD or rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction to explain compression and dominant directions.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <em>Toolbox skills.</em> Compare interior and boundary candidates, set up Lagrange equations, solve small constrained optimization problems, compute <m>A^TA</m>, find singular values and singular vectors, read rank from SVD, identify fundamental subspaces, compute energy retained, interpret rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction, and read low-rank update shapes.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Application and computation outcomes.</em> Interpret Unit 6 computation snippets and Lab U6 <c>[U6-LO4, U6-LO5, U6-LO6, U6-LO7 | C+M+T | Core]</c> by reading SVD shapes, singular values, singular-vector identities, rank and null directions, redundant features, energy retained, rank-<m>k</m> reconstructions, compression on a small matrix, and low-rank update shapes.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <xi:include href="sec-u6-absolute-extrema.ptx" />

  <xi:include href="sec-u6-lagrange-multipliers.ptx" />

  <section xml:id="sec-maximum-stretch-svd">
    <title>Maximum stretch and singular values</title>
    <p>
      One way to ask what a matrix map does is to ask which unit input is stretched the most:
      <me>\max_{\|\mathbf{x}\|=1}\|A\mathbf{x}\|^2.</me>
      The square is included because
      <md>
        <mrow>\|A\mathbf{x}\|^2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = (A\mathbf{x})\cdot(A\mathbf{x})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \mathbf{x}^T A^T A\mathbf{x}.</mrow>
      </md>
      Thus a question about a matrix map becomes a constrained optimization problem for the scalar-valued function
      <me>\mathbf{x}\mapsto \mathbf{x}^T A^T A\mathbf{x}</me>
      on the unit sphere.
    </p>

    <fact xml:id="fact-u6-maximum-stretch-eigenvectors">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>B</m> be a symmetric matrix, and define
          <me>q(\mathbf{x})=\mathbf{x}^T B\mathbf{x}.</me>
          The extrema of <m>q(\mathbf{x})</m> subject to <m>\|\mathbf{x}\|=1</m> occur at eigenvectors of <m>B</m>. The extreme values are eigenvalues of <m>B</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Use the constraint
          <me>g(\mathbf{x})=\mathbf{x}\cdot \mathbf{x}=1.</me>
          For symmetric <m>B</m>,
          <me>\nabla q(\mathbf{x})=2B\mathbf{x},
          \qquad
          \nabla g(\mathbf{x})=2\mathbf{x}.</me>
          The Lagrange multiplier condition gives
          <me>2B\mathbf{x}=\lambda 2\mathbf{x},</me>
          so
          <me>B\mathbf{x}=\lambda \mathbf{x}.</me>
          Thus constrained critical points occur at eigenvectors of <m>B</m>. If <m>\mathbf{x}</m> is a unit eigenvector with <m>B\mathbf{x}=\lambda\mathbf{x}</m>, then
          <md>
            <mrow>q(\mathbf{x}) \amp= \mathbf{x}^T B\mathbf{x}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \mathbf{x}^T(\lambda\mathbf{x})</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \lambda\|\mathbf{x}\|^2</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \lambda.</mrow>
          </md>
          Since the unit sphere is closed and bounded, the extreme value theorem guarantees that the extrema occur among these candidates.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </fact>

    <p>
      Apply the fact to <m>B=A^TA</m>. The eigenvalues of <m>A^TA</m> are nonnegative, so we can take their square roots. The singular values of <m>A</m> are
      <me>\sigma_i=\sqrt{\lambda_i},</me>
      where <m>\lambda_i</m> are the eigenvalues of <m>A^TA</m>, listed so that
      <me>\sigma_1\geq \sigma_2\geq \cdots \geq 0.</me>
      A unit eigenvector of <m>A^TA</m> is a right singular vector of <m>A</m>. The number <m>\sigma_i</m> is the stretch factor in that input direction.
    </p>

    <activity xml:id="act-small-svd-stretch">
      <title>A Small Stretch Computation</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let
          <me>
            A=
            \begin{bmatrix}
            3 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 1
            \end{bmatrix}.
          </me>
          Let
          <me>
            \mathbf{e}_1=
            \begin{bmatrix}
            1\\
            0
            \end{bmatrix},
            \qquad
            \mathbf{e}_2=
            \begin{bmatrix}
            0\\
            1
            \end{bmatrix}.
          </me>
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p>Compute <m>A\mathbf{e}_1</m> and <m>A\mathbf{e}_2</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Compute <m>\|A\mathbf{e}_1\|</m> and <m>\|A\mathbf{e}_2\|</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Compute <m>A^TA</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Find the eigenvalues of <m>A^TA</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>What are the singular values of <m>A</m>?</p></li>
          <li><p>Which unit direction is stretched most?</p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We have
          <me>
            A\mathbf{e}_1=
            \begin{bmatrix}
            3\\
            0
            \end{bmatrix},
            \qquad
            A\mathbf{e}_2=
            \begin{bmatrix}
            0\\
            1
            \end{bmatrix}.
          </me>
          Thus
          <me>
            \|A\mathbf{e}_1\|=3,
            \qquad
            \|A\mathbf{e}_2\|=1.
          </me>
          Also
          <me>
            A^TA=
            \begin{bmatrix}
            3 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 1
            \end{bmatrix}^T
            \begin{bmatrix}
            3 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 1
            \end{bmatrix}
            =
            \begin{bmatrix}
            9 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 1
            \end{bmatrix}.
          </me>
          The eigenvalues of <m>A^TA</m> are <m>9</m> and <m>1</m>. Therefore the singular values of <m>A</m> are
          <me>
            \sigma_1=3,
            \qquad
            \sigma_2=1.
          </me>
          The direction <m>\mathbf{e}_1</m> is stretched most. This is the simplest version of the question
          <me>\max_{\|\mathbf{x}\|=1}\|A\mathbf{x}\|.</me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>

    <activity xml:id="act-u6-reading-maximum-stretch-code">
      <title>Reading the same stretch in code</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The following code repeats the previous activity using <m>A^TA</m>.
        </p>
        <program language="python"><code><![CDATA[import numpy as np

A = np.array([[3., 0.],
              [0., 1.]])

B = A.T @ A
eigvals, eigvecs = np.linalg.eigh(B)

singular_values = np.sqrt(eigvals[::-1])
dominant_direction = eigvecs[:, -1]

B, eigvals, singular_values, dominant_direction
]]></code></program>
        <p>Output:</p>
        <pre><![CDATA[(array([[9., 0.],
        [0., 1.]]),
 array([1., 9.]),
 array([3., 1.]),
 array([1., 0.]))]]></pre>
        <ol>
          <li><p>What mathematical matrix is stored in <c>B</c>?</p></li>
          <li><p>Why are the entries of <c>eigvals</c> squared stretch factors?</p></li>
          <li><p>Why does the code take a square root?</p></li>
          <li><p>Why does <c>eigvecs[:, -1]</c> give the most-stretched input direction?</p></li>
          <li><p>What value of <m>\max_{\|\mathbf{x}\|=1}\|A\mathbf{x}\|</m> does the code predict?</p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The matrix <c>B</c> is <m>A^TA</m>. The entries of <c>eigvals</c> are eigenvalues of <m>A^TA</m>, so they are values of <m>\|A\mathbf{x}\|^2</m> for special unit input directions. The code takes a square root because singular values measure <m>\|A\mathbf{x}\|</m>, not <m>\|A\mathbf{x}\|^2</m>. The command <c>np.linalg.eigh</c> lists eigenvalues in increasing order, so the largest eigenvalue is last, and <c>eigvecs[:, -1]</c> is its eigenvector. The largest singular value is <m>3</m>, so
          <me>\max_{\|\mathbf{x}\|=1}\|A\mathbf{x}\|=3.</me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>

    <p>
      The next section packages these ingredients into one factorization. The right singular vectors are special input directions. The singular values are stretch factors. Multiplying a right singular vector by <m>A</m> gives the corresponding output direction.
    </p>
  </section>

  <xi:include href="sec-u6-singular-value-decomposition.ptx" />

  <section xml:id="sec-u6-svd-information-channels">
    <title>Low-rank approximation and compression</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        <em>Application question.</em> How can a matrix be approximated by keeping only its strongest directions?
      </p>
      <p>
        The SVD writes a matrix map as a sum of directional pieces. If
        <me>A=U\Sigma V^T</me>
        has rank <m>r</m>, then
        <me>
          A
          =
          \sum_{i=1}^r \sigma_i\mathbf{u}_i\mathbf{v}_i^T.
        </me>
        The matrix
        <me>\sigma_i\mathbf{u}_i\mathbf{v}_i^T</me>
        has rank one. It measures the input coordinate in the direction <m>\mathbf{v}_i</m>, stretches by <m>\sigma_i</m>, and sends the result in the output direction <m>\mathbf{u}_i</m>.
      </p>

      <definition xml:id="def-u6-rank-k-reconstruction">
        <title>Rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let
            <me>A=U\Sigma V^T</me>
            be an SVD of a rank-<m>r</m> matrix <m>A</m>. For <m>1\leq k\leq r</m>, the rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction of <m>A</m> is
            <me>
              A_k
              =
              U_k\Sigma_kV_k^T
              =
              \sum_{i=1}^k \sigma_i\mathbf{u}_i\mathbf{v}_i^T,
            </me>
            where <m>U_k</m> contains the first <m>k</m> columns of <m>U</m>, <m>\Sigma_k</m> contains the first <m>k</m> singular values, and <m>V_k</m> contains the first <m>k</m> columns of <m>V</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The matrix <m>A_k</m> keeps the <m>k</m> largest singular directions and discards the rest. Its rank is at most <m>k</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <activity xml:id="act-u6-rank-one-diagonal-stretch">
        <title>Rank-one reconstruction of a diagonal stretch</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Return to the diagonal stretch from Section 6.3:
            <me>
              A=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                3 \amp 0\\
                0 \amp 1
              \end{bmatrix}.
            </me>
            For this matrix, the right and left singular vectors are
            <me>
              \mathbf{e}_1=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1\\
                0
              \end{bmatrix},
              \qquad
              \mathbf{e}_2=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                0\\
                1
              \end{bmatrix},
            </me>
            and the singular values are
            <me>
              \sigma_1=3,
              \qquad
              \sigma_2=1.
            </me>
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li><p>Write <m>A</m> as
              <me>3\mathbf{e}_1\mathbf{e}_1^T+\mathbf{e}_2\mathbf{e}_2^T.</me></p></li>
            <li><p>Compute the rank-one reconstruction
              <me>A_1=3\mathbf{e}_1\mathbf{e}_1^T.</me></p></li>
            <li><p>For
              <me>
                \mathbf{x}=
                \begin{bmatrix}
                  a\\
                  b
                \end{bmatrix},
              </me>
              compute <m>A\mathbf{x}</m> and <m>A_1\mathbf{x}</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Which input direction is discarded by <m>A_1</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What is <m>\operatorname{rank}(A_1)</m>?</p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We have
            <md>
              <mrow>\mathbf{e}_1\mathbf{e}_1^T</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp =
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1\\
                0
              \end{bmatrix}
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1 \amp 0
              \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp =
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1 \amp 0\\
                0 \amp 0
              \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
            </md>
            and
            <md>
              <mrow>\mathbf{e}_2\mathbf{e}_2^T</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp =
              \begin{bmatrix}
                0\\
                1
              \end{bmatrix}
              \begin{bmatrix}
                0 \amp 1
              \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp =
              \begin{bmatrix}
                0 \amp 0\\
                0 \amp 1
              \end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
            </md>
            Thus
            <md>
              <mrow>3\mathbf{e}_1\mathbf{e}_1^T+\mathbf{e}_2\mathbf{e}_2^T</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp =
              3
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1 \amp 0\\
                0 \amp 0
              \end{bmatrix}
              +
              \begin{bmatrix}
                0 \amp 0\\
                0 \amp 1
              \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp =
              \begin{bmatrix}
                3 \amp 0\\
                0 \amp 1
              \end{bmatrix}
              =
              A.</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            The rank-one reconstruction is
            <me>
              A_1
              =
              3\mathbf{e}_1\mathbf{e}_1^T
              =
              \begin{bmatrix}
                3 \amp 0\\
                0 \amp 0
              \end{bmatrix}.
            </me>
            Therefore
            <md>
              <mrow>
              A
              \begin{bmatrix}
                a\\
                b
              \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp =
              \begin{bmatrix}
                3a\\
                b
              \end{bmatrix},</mrow>
              <mrow>
              A_1
              \begin{bmatrix}
                a\\
                b
              \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp =
              \begin{bmatrix}
                3a\\
                0
              \end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
            </md>
            The rank-one reconstruction keeps the <m>\mathbf{e}_1</m> direction and discards the <m>\mathbf{e}_2</m> direction. The rank of <m>A_1</m> is <m>1</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </activity>

      <note xml:id="note-u6-energy-retained">
        <title>Energy retained</title>
        <p>
          A common way to summarize how much of a matrix has been kept is to use squared singular values. The energy retained by the first <m>k</m> singular values is
          <me>
            \frac{\sigma_1^2+\cdots+\sigma_k^2}
            {\sigma_1^2+\cdots+\sigma_r^2}.
          </me>
          This number is between <m>0</m> and <m>1</m>. Larger values mean that the rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction keeps more of the matrix's dominant directions.
        </p>
      </note>

      <activity xml:id="act-u6-choosing-k-singular-values">
        <title>Choosing <m>k</m> from singular values</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose the nonzero singular values of a matrix are
            <me>10,\ 4,\ 1,\ 0.5,\ 0.1.</me>
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li><p>Compute the total squared singular-value energy.</p></li>
            <li><p>Compute the energy retained by <m>k=1</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Compute the energy retained by <m>k=2</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>What is the smallest <m>k</m> that retains at least <m>90\%</m> of the energy?</p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The squared singular values are
            <me>100,\ 16,\ 1,\ 0.25,\ 0.01.</me>
            The total squared energy is
            <me>100+16+1+0.25+0.01=117.26.</me>
          </p>
          <p>
            For <m>k=1</m>, the retained energy is
            <me>\frac{100}{117.26}\approx 0.853.</me>
            For <m>k=2</m>, the retained energy is
            <me>
              \frac{100+16}{117.26}
              =
              \frac{116}{117.26}
              \approx 0.989.
            </me>
            Thus <m>k=2</m> is the smallest value that retains at least <m>90\%</m> of the energy.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </activity>
    </introduction>

    <note xml:id="sec-u6-code-rank-k">
      <title>Rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction in NumPy</title>
      <p>
        In NumPy, the singular values are returned as a one-dimensional array <c>s</c>. The diagonal matrix <m>\Sigma_k</m> is built from <c>s[:k]</c>.
      </p>
      <program language="python"><code><![CDATA[U, s, Vt = np.linalg.svd(A, full_matrices=False)
Ak = U[:, :k] @ np.diag(s[:k]) @ Vt[:k, :]
]]></code></program>
      <p>
        The matrix <c>U[:, :k]</c> keeps the first <m>k</m> left singular vectors. The matrix <c>Vt[:k, :]</c> keeps the first <m>k</m> rows of <m>V^T</m>, which correspond to the first <m>k</m> right singular vectors. The product <c>Ak</c> is the rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction.
      </p>
      <p>
        For a quick reference on SVD commands, diagonal matrices, slices, and matrix multiplication, see the programming appendix sections <xref ref="appcomp-numpy-linalg" text="global"/>, <xref ref="appcomp-array-constructors" text="global"/>, <xref ref="appcomp-indexing-slicing" text="global"/>, and <xref ref="appcomp-elementwise-vs-linear-algebra" text="global"/>.
      </p>
    </note>

    <conclusion>
      <activity xml:id="act-u6-reading-rank-k-code">
        <title>Reading rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction code</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The following code computes a rank-one reconstruction of the diagonal stretch.
          </p>
          <program language="python"><code><![CDATA[import numpy as np

A = np.array([[3., 0.],
              [0., 1.]])

U, s, Vt = np.linalg.svd(A, full_matrices=False)

k = 1
Ak = U[:, :k] @ np.diag(s[:k]) @ Vt[:k, :]

s, Ak
]]></code></program>
          <p>Output:</p>
          <pre><![CDATA[(array([3., 1.]),
 array([[3., 0.],
        [0., 0.]]))]]></pre>
          <ol>
            <li><p>What are the singular values of <m>A</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>Which singular value is kept when <m>k=1</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What is the matrix <m>A_1</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>Which input direction does <m>A_1</m> discard?</p></li>
            <li><p>Why is <c>Vt[:k, :]</c> used instead of <c>Vt[:, :k]</c>?</p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The singular values are <m>3</m> and <m>1</m>. When <m>k=1</m>, the reconstruction keeps only the singular value <m>3</m>. The reconstructed matrix is
            <me>
              A_1=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                3 \amp 0\\
                0 \amp 0
              \end{bmatrix}.
            </me>
            It discards the second input direction. The slice <c>Vt[:k, :]</c> keeps the first <m>k</m> rows of <m>V^T</m>, which are the transposed right singular vectors used in the reconstruction. The slice <c>Vt[:, :k]</c> would keep columns of <m>V^T</m>, which is the wrong shape and the wrong mathematical object for this product.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </activity>

      <activity xml:id="act-u6-redundant-features-singular-values">
        <title>Redundant features revisited by singular values</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Return to the redundant-feature matrix from Unit 2:
            <me>
              X=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\
                2 \amp 4 \amp 6\\
                0 \amp 1 \amp 1\\
                1 \amp -1 \amp 0
              \end{bmatrix}.
            </me>
            The third column is the sum of the first two columns.
          </p>
          <p>
            The following code computes the singular values and the last row of <m>V^T</m>.
          </p>
          <program language="python"><code><![CDATA[import numpy as np

np.set_printoptions(precision=3, suppress=True)

X = np.array([[1.,  2., 3.],
              [2.,  4., 6.],
              [0.,  1., 1.],
              [1., -1., 0.]])

U, s, Vt = np.linalg.svd(X, full_matrices=False)

s, Vt[-1, :]
]]></code></program>
          <p>Output:</p>
          <pre><![CDATA[(array([8.478, 1.459, 0.   ]),
 array([-0.577, -0.577,  0.577]))]]></pre>
          <ol>
            <li><p>What does the zero singular value say about the rank of <m>X</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What null-space direction does the last row of <m>V^T</m> point along?</p></li>
            <li><p>How does this match the Unit 2 relation among the columns?</p></li>
            <li><p>If <m>X\mathbf{c}=\mathbf{y}</m>, what happens to <m>X(\mathbf{c}+t\mathbf{z})</m>, where
              <me>
                \mathbf{z}=
                \begin{bmatrix}
                  1\\
                  1\\
                  -1
                \end{bmatrix}?
              </me></p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The zero singular value says that the three columns of <m>X</m> contain only two independent directions, so
            <me>\operatorname{rank}(X)=2.</me>
            The last row of <m>V^T</m> is approximately
            <me>
              \begin{bmatrix}
                -0.577 \amp -0.577 \amp 0.577
              \end{bmatrix},
            </me>
            which points in the same direction as
            <me>
              -\frac{1}{\sqrt3}
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1\\
                1\\
                -1
              \end{bmatrix}.
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            This matches the Unit 2 relation
            <me>\text{column }1+\text{column }2-\text{column }3=\mathbf{0},</me>
            or
            <me>
              X
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1\\
                1\\
                -1
              \end{bmatrix}
              =
              \mathbf{0}.
            </me>
            Therefore, if <m>X\mathbf{c}=\mathbf{y}</m>, then
            <md>
              <mrow>X(\mathbf{c}+t\mathbf{z})</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp =
              X\mathbf{c}+tX\mathbf{z}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp =
              \mathbf{y}.</mrow>
            </md>
            The null direction gives different coefficient vectors with the same output.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </activity>

      <note xml:id="ai-u6-low-rank-updates">
        <title>Low-rank updates</title>
        <p>
          A low-rank update changes a large matrix by adding a product
          <me>BC,</me>
          where
          <me>
            B\in\mathbb R^{m\times r},
            \qquad
            C\in\mathbb R^{r\times n},
          </me>
          and <m>r</m> is small. Since
          <me>\operatorname{rank}(BC)\leq r,</me>
          the update <m>BC</m> changes the matrix through at most <m>r</m> independent directions.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is useful when a full <m>m\times n</m> matrix would be expensive to store or change. The matrix <m>BC</m> can be stored using
          <me>mr+rn</me>
          numbers instead of <m>mn</m> numbers.
        </p>
        <p>
          In model-adaptation settings, <m>W</m> may be a large existing weight matrix and <m>BC</m> may represent a small trainable update. The linear-algebra point is independent of that application: the update <m>BC</m> has rank at most <m>r</m> and can be stored using many fewer numbers than a full <m>m\times n</m> matrix.
        </p>
      </note>

      <activity xml:id="act-u6-rank-low-rank-update">
        <title>Rank of an update</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let
            <me>
              W\in\mathbb R^{1000\times 800},
              \qquad
              B\in\mathbb R^{1000\times 4},
              \qquad
              C\in\mathbb R^{4\times 800}.
            </me>
            Define
            <me>W_{\text{new}}=W+BC.</me>
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li><p>What is the shape of <m>BC</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What is the largest possible rank of <m>BC</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>How many numbers are needed to store <m>W</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>How many numbers are needed to store <m>B</m> and <m>C</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>Why is <m>BC</m> called a low-rank update?</p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The product <m>BC</m> has shape
            <me>1000\times 800,</me>
            so it can be added to <m>W</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The rank of a product is at most the inner dimension, so
            <me>\operatorname{rank}(BC)\leq 4.</me>
            The full matrix <m>W</m> stores
            <me>1000\cdot 800=800000</me>
            numbers. The two update matrices store
            <me>1000\cdot 4+4\cdot 800=4000+3200=7200</me>
            numbers.
          </p>
          <p>
            The update is called low-rank because the change <m>BC</m> has rank at most <m>4</m>, even though it has the same shape as <m>W</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </activity>

      <warning xml:id="warn-u6-low-rank-update-not-low-rank-matrix">
        <title>Low-rank update versus low-rank matrix</title>
        <p>
          A low-rank update does not mean that the whole matrix
          <me>W_{\text{new}}=W+BC</me>
          has low rank. The update <m>BC</m> has rank at most <m>r</m>. The matrix <m>W+BC</m> may still have large rank.
        </p>
      </warning>
    </conclusion>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-u6-apps-computation">
    <title>Applications and computation recap</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        This section checks whether you can read the computations already used in Unit 6.
      </p>
      <p>
        A short SVD computation should be read in three steps.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Identify the shapes.</p></li>
        <li><p>Identify the singular directions or singular values being used.</p></li>
        <li><p>Interpret what is kept, weakened, or discarded.</p></li>
      </ol>
      <table xml:id="tab-u6-reading-svd-computations">
        <title>Reading SVD computations</title>
        <tabular>
          <col width="28%"/>
          <col width="30%"/>
          <col width="34%"/>
          <row header="yes"><cell><p>Code fragment</p></cell><cell><p>First question to ask</p></cell><cell><p>Typical interpretation</p></cell></row>
          <row><cell><c>U, s, Vt = np.linalg.svd(A, full_matrices=False)</c></cell><cell><p>What are the shapes of <c>U</c>, <c>s</c>, and <c>Vt</c>?</p></cell><cell><p>reduced SVD</p></cell></row>
          <row><cell><c>A.T @ A</c></cell><cell><p>Which input directions does this matrix analyze?</p></cell><cell><p>eigenvectors give right singular directions</p></cell></row>
          <row><cell><c>s</c></cell><cell><p>Are the values sorted?</p></cell><cell><p>singular values, largest first</p></cell></row>
          <row><cell><c>s**2</c></cell><cell><p>Why squares?</p></cell><cell><p>eigenvalues of <m>A^TA</m> and squared stretch factors</p></cell></row>
          <row><cell><c>np.cumsum(s**2)/np.sum(s**2)</c></cell><cell><p>How much energy is kept after <m>k</m> terms?</p></cell><cell><p>cumulative energy retained</p></cell></row>
          <row><cell><c>U[:, :k]</c></cell><cell><p>Which output directions are kept?</p></cell><cell><p>first <m>k</m> left singular vectors</p></cell></row>
          <row><cell><c>Vt[:k, :]</c></cell><cell><p>Which input directions are kept?</p></cell><cell><p>first <m>k</m> transposed right singular vectors</p></cell></row>
          <row><cell><c>U[:, :k] @ np.diag(s[:k]) @ Vt[:k, :]</c></cell><cell><p>What rank should this have?</p></cell><cell><p>rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction</p></cell></row>
          <row><cell><c>A @ Vt.T[:, i]</c></cell><cell><p>What should this equal?</p></cell><cell><p><m>\sigma_i\mathbf{u}_i</m></p></cell></row>
          <row><cell><p><c>Vt[-1, :]</c> with a small last singular value</p></cell><cell><p>Is this exact or numerical?</p></cell><cell><p>approximate forgotten input direction</p></cell></row>
          <row><cell><p><c>B @ C</c> with <m>B\in\mathbb R^{m\times r}</m>, <m>C\in\mathbb R^{r\times n}</m></p></cell><cell><p>What is the largest possible rank?</p></cell><cell><p>low-rank update</p></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
    </introduction>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-u6-review-activities">
      <title>Review activities</title>

      <activity xml:id="act-u6-recap-svd-shapes">
        <title>Reading SVD shapes</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The following code computes a reduced SVD.
          </p>
          <program language="python"><code><![CDATA[import numpy as np

A = np.array([[ 1., -1.],
              [-2.,  2.],
              [ 2., -2.]])

U, s, Vt = np.linalg.svd(A, full_matrices=False)

A.shape, U.shape, s.shape, Vt.shape
]]></code></program>
          <p>Output:</p>
          <pre><![CDATA[((3, 2), (3, 2), (2,), (2, 2))]]></pre>
          <ol>
            <li><p>What is the shape of <m>A</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>How many singular values are returned?</p></li>
            <li><p>Why is <c>s.shape</c> equal to <c>(2,)</c> rather than <c>(2, 2)</c>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What matrix does <c>Vt</c> represent?</p></li>
            <li><p>What does <c>full_matrices=False</c> do in this example?</p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The matrix <m>A</m> is <m>3\times 2</m>. The reduced SVD returns two singular values because
            <me>\min(3,2)=2.</me>
            The array <c>s</c> stores only the diagonal entries of <m>\Sigma</m>, not the full diagonal matrix, so its shape is <c>(2,)</c>. The array <c>Vt</c> represents <m>V^T</m>. With <c>full_matrices=False</c>, NumPy returns the reduced SVD shapes needed for reconstruction:
            <me>
              U\in\mathbb R^{3\times 2},
              \qquad
              s\in\mathbb R^2,
              \qquad
              V^T\in\mathbb R^{2\times 2}.
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </activity>

      <activity xml:id="act-u6-recap-singular-vector-identity">
        <title>Checking a singular-vector identity in code</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For an SVD
            <me>A=U\Sigma V^T,</me>
            the identity
            <me>A\mathbf{v}_i=\sigma_i\mathbf{u}_i</me>
            is one of the main ways to read the factors. The following code checks this identity for a diagonal stretch.
          </p>
          <program language="python"><code><![CDATA[A = np.array([[3., 0.],
              [0., 1.]])

U, s, Vt = np.linalg.svd(A, full_matrices=False)

i = 0
v = Vt.T[:, i]
lhs = A @ v
rhs = s[i] * U[:, i]

lhs, rhs, np.allclose(lhs, rhs)
]]></code></program>
          <p>Output:</p>
          <pre><![CDATA[(array([3., 0.]), array([3., 0.]), True)]]></pre>
          <ol>
            <li><p>Which vector is stored in <c>v</c>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What does <c>lhs</c> compute?</p></li>
            <li><p>What does <c>rhs</c> compute?</p></li>
            <li><p>Why does <c>np.allclose(lhs, rhs)</c> return <c>True</c>?</p></li>
            <li><p>Which stretch factor appears in this computation?</p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The vector <c>v</c> is the first right singular vector <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m>. The array <c>lhs</c> computes <m>A\mathbf{v}_1</m>. The array <c>rhs</c> computes <m>\sigma_1\mathbf{u}_1</m>. The value <c>True</c> means that the numerical computation agrees with
            <me>A\mathbf{v}_1=\sigma_1\mathbf{u}_1.</me>
            The stretch factor is
            <me>\sigma_1=3.</me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </activity>

      <activity xml:id="act-u6-recap-energy-retained">
        <title>Reading energy retained</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The following code computes cumulative energy retained from a list of singular values.
          </p>
          <program language="python"><code><![CDATA[np.set_printoptions(precision=4, suppress=True)

s = np.array([10., 4., 1., 0.2])
energy = np.cumsum(s**2) / np.sum(s**2)

energy
]]></code></program>
          <p>Output:</p>
          <pre><![CDATA[array([0.8544, 0.9911, 0.9997, 1.    ])]]></pre>
          <ol>
            <li><p>Why does the code use <c>s**2</c>?</p></li>
            <li><p>How much energy is retained by <m>k=1</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>How much energy is retained by <m>k=2</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What is the smallest <m>k</m> that retains at least <m>90\%</m> of the energy?</p></li>
            <li><p>What is discarded in a rank-2 reconstruction?</p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Squared singular values measure squared stretch and are used for the energy calculation. For <m>k=1</m>, the retained energy is approximately
            <me>0.8544.</me>
            For <m>k=2</m>, the retained energy is approximately
            <me>0.9911.</me>
            The smallest <m>k</m> retaining at least <m>90\%</m> of the energy is
            <me>k=2.</me>
            A rank-2 reconstruction keeps the directions corresponding to singular values <m>10</m> and <m>4</m>, and discards the smaller directions corresponding to singular values <m>1</m> and <m>0.2</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </activity>

      <activity xml:id="act-u6-recap-debugging-svd-slice">
        <title>Debugging an SVD slice</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A student tries to compute a rank-one reconstruction using this code.
          </p>
          <program language="python"><code><![CDATA[A = np.array([[3., 0.],
              [0., 1.]])

U, s, Vt = np.linalg.svd(A, full_matrices=False)

k = 1
Ak_wrong = U[:, :k] @ np.diag(s[:k]) @ Vt[:, :k]
]]></code></program>
          <ol>
            <li><p>Which slice is wrong?</p></li>
            <li><p>What should the last slice be?</p></li>
            <li><p>What shape problem appears when <m>A</m> is <m>2\times 2</m> and <m>k=1</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What is the mathematical mistake?</p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The wrong slice is <c>Vt[:, :k]</c>. The reconstruction should use <c>Vt[:k, :]</c>. When <m>A</m> is <m>2\times 2</m> and <m>k=1</m>, the shapes are
            <me>
              U[:, :1]\in\mathbb R^{2\times 1},
              \qquad
              \operatorname{diag}(s[:1])\in\mathbb R^{1\times 1},
              \qquad
              Vt[:, :1]\in\mathbb R^{2\times 1}.
            </me>
            After the first two factors are multiplied, the result has shape <m>2\times 1</m>, which cannot be multiplied by a <m>2\times 1</m> matrix on the right.
          </p>
          <p>
            The mathematical mistake is that columns of <m>V^T</m> are not the transposed right singular vectors used in the reconstruction. The rows of <m>V^T</m> are the transposed right singular vectors, so the correct slice is <c>Vt[:k, :]</c>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </activity>

      <activity xml:id="act-u6-recap-low-rank-update-shape">
        <title>Reading a low-rank update shape</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The following code counts storage for a low-rank update.
          </p>
          <program language="python"><code><![CDATA[m, n, r = 1000, 800, 4

W_shape = (m, n)
B_shape = (m, r)
C_shape = (r, n)
update_shape = (m, n)

storage_update = m*r + r*n
storage_full = m*n

W_shape, B_shape, C_shape, update_shape, storage_update, storage_full
]]></code></program>
          <p>Output:</p>
          <pre><![CDATA[((1000, 800), (1000, 4), (4, 800), (1000, 800), 7200, 800000)]]></pre>
          <ol>
            <li><p>What is the shape of <m>W</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What is the shape of <m>BC</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What is the largest possible rank of <m>BC</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>How many numbers are needed to store <m>B</m> and <m>C</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>How many numbers are needed to store a full <m>1000\times 800</m> matrix?</p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The matrix <m>W</m> has shape
            <me>1000\times 800.</me>
            Since
            <me>
              B\in\mathbb R^{1000\times 4},
              \qquad
              C\in\mathbb R^{4\times 800},
            </me>
            the product <m>BC</m> has shape
            <me>1000\times 800.</me>
            Its rank is at most <m>4</m>. The matrices <m>B</m> and <m>C</m> require
            <me>1000\cdot 4+4\cdot 800=7200</me>
            numbers. A full <m>1000\times 800</m> matrix requires
            <me>1000\cdot 800=800000</me>
            numbers.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </activity>
    </subsection>

    <conclusion>
      <note xml:id="lab-u6-callout">
        <title>Linked notebook</title>
        <p>
          Run <url href="https://sebroc.github.io/MATH345-Course-Materials/labs/#lab-u6">Lab U6: SVD and Compression</url>. The core path practices SVD shapes, singular values, singular-vector identities, rank and null directions, redundant features, energy retained, rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction, compression on a small matrix, low-rank update shapes, and review code-reading checks. The activities above prepare you to read the notebook outputs as mathematical statements.
        </p>
        <p>
          For a quick reference on SVD commands, diagonal matrices, slices, matrix multiplication, and numerical checks such as <c>np.allclose</c>, see the programming appendix sections <xref ref="appcomp-numpy-linalg" text="global"/>, <xref ref="appcomp-array-constructors" text="global"/>, <xref ref="appcomp-indexing-slicing" text="global"/>, <xref ref="appcomp-elementwise-vs-linear-algebra" text="global"/>, and <xref ref="appcomp-numerical-checks" text="global"/>.
        </p>
      </note>
      <p>
        <em>Interpretation check.</em> Given singular values, choose <m>k</m> to retain a specified percentage of energy. Explain what information is discarded when small singular values are removed. <em>Tags.</em> <c>[U6-LO6, U6-LO7 | C+M+T | Core]</c>
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Exam-style check.</em> The singular values are
        <me>10,\ 4,\ 1,\ 0.2.</me>
        Which directions are most important, and what is discarded in a rank-2 approximation? <em>Tags.</em> <c>[U6-LO6, U6-LO7 | C+M | Core]</c>
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Exam skill.</em> Read a short SVD computation and explain singular values, rank, retained energy, forgotten directions, and rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction without coding the SVD from scratch. <em>Tags.</em> <c>[U6-LO4, U6-LO5, U6-LO6, U6-LO7 | C+M+T | Core]</c>
      </p>
    </conclusion>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="u6-exercises">
    <title>Exercises</title>
