    <subsection xml:id="u6-exercises-sec-singular-value-decomposition">
      <title>Singular value decomposition</title>
      <p><em>Primary outcomes.</em> U6-LO3, U6-LO4, U6-LO5, U6-LO6. <em>Competencies.</em> P+C.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><url href="https://math.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/Linear_Algebra_with_Applications_(Nicholson)/08%3A_Orthogonality/8.06%3A_The_Singular_Value_Decomposition/8.6E%3A_The_Singular_Value_Decomposition_Exercises">Nicholson 8.6.9(b)</url></p></li>
      </ul>
    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="u6-exercises-applied-computational">
      <title>Additional applied and computational problems</title>
      <p>
        These exercises connect the main Unit 6 ideas: absolute extrema on closed bounded regions, Lagrange multipliers, maximum stretch, singular values, SVD, fundamental subspaces, rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction, energy retained, redundant features, low-rank updates, and code interpretation. Solutions are collected in Appendix <xref ref="app-u6-applied-solutions" text="global"/>.
      </p>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-u6-checkpoint-candidate-table-rectangle">
        <title>Candidate table on a rectangle</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let
            <me>f(x,y)=x^2+y^2-2x+4y</me>
            on the rectangle
            <me>D=\{(x,y):0\leq x\leq 3,\ -3\leq y\leq 1\}.</me>
          </p>
          <ol marker="a">
            <li><p>Find the critical point of <m>f</m> in the interior of <m>D</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Find the boundary candidates on each of the four edges.</p></li>
            <li><p>Include the four corner points.</p></li>
            <li><p>Make a candidate table with the source of each candidate and the value of <m>f</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Find the absolute maximum and absolute minimum of <m>f</m> on <m>D</m>.</p></li>
          </ol>
          <p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U6-LO1 | P+C+R | Core]</c></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-u6-checkpoint-parallel-gradients-circle">
        <title>Parallel gradients on a circle</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let
            <me>f(x,y)=3x+4y</me>
            and constrain the input to the circle
            <me>x^2+y^2=25.</me>
          </p>
          <ol marker="a">
            <li><p>Write the constraint as <m>g(x,y)=25</m>.</p></li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Solve
                <me>\nabla f=\lambda\nabla g.</me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li><p>Find the constrained critical points.</p></li>
            <li><p>Evaluate <m>f</m> at the constrained critical points.</p></li>
            <li><p>Which point gives the absolute maximum? Which point gives the absolute minimum?</p></li>
            <li><p>Explain geometrically why <m>\nabla f</m> is parallel to <m>\nabla g</m> at those points.</p></li>
          </ol>
          <p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U6-LO2 | P+C+R | Core]</c></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-u6-checkpoint-quadratic-form-unit-circle">
        <title>Quadratic form on the unit circle</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let
            <me>
              B=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                5\amp 0\\
                0\amp 2
              \end{bmatrix}
            </me>
            and
            <me>q(\mathbf{x})=\mathbf{x}^TB\mathbf{x}.</me>
            Write
            <me>
              \mathbf{x}=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                x\\
                y
              \end{bmatrix}.
            </me>
          </p>
          <ol marker="a">
            <li><p>Write <m>q(\mathbf{x})</m> in terms of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.</p></li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Maximize <m>q(\mathbf{x})</m> subject to
                <me>\|\mathbf{x}\|=1.</me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Minimize <m>q(\mathbf{x})</m> subject to
                <me>\|\mathbf{x}\|=1.</me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li><p>Which unit vectors give the extreme values?</p></li>
            <li><p>How do the answers relate to eigenvalues and eigenvectors of <m>B</m>?</p></li>
          </ol>
          <p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U6-LO2, U6-LO3 | P+C+R | Core]</c></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-u6-checkpoint-maximum-stretch-matrix">
        <title>Maximum stretch of a matrix</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let
            <me>
              A=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1\amp 2\\
                2\amp 1
              \end{bmatrix}.
            </me>
          </p>
          <ol marker="a">
            <li><p>Compute <m>A^TA</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Find the eigenvalues of <m>A^TA</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Find the singular values of <m>A</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Find a unit right singular vector corresponding to the largest singular value.</p></li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What is
                <me>\max_{\|\mathbf{x}\|=1}\|A\mathbf{x}\|?</me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li><p>Which input direction is stretched most?</p></li>
          </ol>
          <p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U6-LO3, U6-LO6 | P+C+R | Core]</c></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-u6-checkpoint-reading-svd">
        <title>Reading an SVD</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose
            <me>A=U\Sigma V^T,</me>
            where
            <me>
              U=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1\amp 0\\
                0\amp 1
              \end{bmatrix},
              \qquad
              \Sigma=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                5\amp 0\amp 0\\
                0\amp 2\amp 0
              \end{bmatrix},
            </me>
            and
            <me>
              V=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1/\sqrt2\amp 0\amp 1/\sqrt2\\
                1/\sqrt2\amp 0\amp -1/\sqrt2\\
                0\amp 1\amp 0
              \end{bmatrix}.
            </me>
            Thus the right singular vectors are
            <me>
              \mathbf{v}_1=
              \frac{1}{\sqrt2}
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1\\
                1\\
                0
              \end{bmatrix},
              \qquad
              \mathbf{v}_2=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                0\\
                0\\
                1
              \end{bmatrix},
              \qquad
              \mathbf{v}_3=
              \frac{1}{\sqrt2}
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1\\
                -1\\
                0
              \end{bmatrix}.
            </me>
          </p>
          <ol marker="a">
            <li><p>What are the singular values of <m>A</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What is <m>\operatorname{rank}(A)</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>Compute <m>A\mathbf{v}_1</m>, <m>A\mathbf{v}_2</m>, and <m>A\mathbf{v}_3</m> using the SVD.</p></li>
            <li><p>Which input direction is forgotten?</p></li>
            <li><p>Which input directions are transmitted?</p></li>
          </ol>
          <p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U6-LO4, U6-LO5, U6-LO6 | C+R | Core]</c></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-u6-checkpoint-fundamental-subspaces-svd">
        <title>Fundamental subspaces from an SVD</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the SVD data from the previous checkpoint.
          </p>
          <ol marker="a">
            <li><p>Give an orthonormal basis for <m>\operatorname{row}(A)</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Give an orthonormal basis for <m>\operatorname{null}(A)</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Give an orthonormal basis for <m>\operatorname{col}(A)</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Give an orthonormal basis for <m>\operatorname{null}(A^T)</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Check that the dimensions agree with rank-nullity.</p></li>
          </ol>
          <p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U6-LO5 | C+R | Core]</c></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-u6-checkpoint-energy-retained">
        <title>Energy retained</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose the nonzero singular values of a matrix are
            <me>10,\ 4,\ 1,\ 0.5.</me>
          </p>
          <ol marker="a">
            <li><p>Compute the total squared singular-value energy.</p></li>
            <li><p>Compute the energy retained by <m>k=1</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Compute the energy retained by <m>k=2</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Find the smallest <m>k</m> that retains at least <m>95\%</m> of the energy.</p></li>
            <li><p>Explain what is discarded by that rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction.</p></li>
          </ol>
          <p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U6-LO6, U6-LO7 | C+M | Core]</c></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-u6-checkpoint-code-rank-k-reconstruction">
        <title>Code interpretation: rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The following code computes a rank-one reconstruction.
          </p>
          <program language="python"><code><![CDATA[import numpy as np

A = np.array([[3., 0.],
              [0., 1.]])

U, s, Vt = np.linalg.svd(A, full_matrices=False)

k = 1
Ak = U[:, :k] @ np.diag(s[:k]) @ Vt[:k, :]

s, Ak
]]></code></program>
          <ol marker="a">
            <li><p>What are the singular values of <m>A</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>Which singular value is kept when <m>k=1</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What is the shape of <c>U[:, :k]</c>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What is the shape of <c>np.diag(s[:k])</c>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What is the shape of <c>Vt[:k, :]</c>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What is the rank of <c>Ak</c>?</p></li>
            <li><p>Which input direction is discarded?</p></li>
          </ol>
          <p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U6-LO4, U6-LO7 | R+T | Core]</c></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-u6-checkpoint-debugging-svd-slice">
        <title>Debugging an SVD slice</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A student tries to compute a rank-one reconstruction using this code.
          </p>
          <program language="python"><code><![CDATA[A = np.array([[3., 0.],
              [0., 1.]])

U, s, Vt = np.linalg.svd(A, full_matrices=False)

k = 1
Ak_wrong = U[:, :k] @ np.diag(s[:k]) @ Vt[:, :k]
]]></code></program>
          <ol marker="a">
            <li><p>Which slice is wrong?</p></li>
            <li><p>What should the last slice be?</p></li>
            <li><p>Explain the shape problem.</p></li>
            <li><p>Explain the mathematical problem.</p></li>
          </ol>
          <p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U6-LO4, U6-LO7 | C+T | Core]</c></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-u6-checkpoint-redundant-features-singular-values">
        <title>Redundant features revisited by singular values</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Return to the Unit 2 redundant-feature matrix
            <me>
              X=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1\amp 2\amp 3\\
                2\amp 4\amp 6\\
                0\amp 1\amp 1\\
                1\amp -1\amp 0
              \end{bmatrix}.
            </me>
            The third column is the sum of the first two columns.
          </p>
          <ol marker="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                Verify that
                <me>
                  X
                  \begin{bmatrix}
                    1\\
                    1\\
                    -1
                  \end{bmatrix}
                  =
                  \mathbf{0}.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li><p>What does this say about <m>\operatorname{null}(X)</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What does this say about the rank of <m>X</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What singular value should appear because of this redundancy?</p></li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>X\mathbf{c}=\mathbf{y}</m>, what is
                <me>
                  X\left(\mathbf{c}+t
                  \begin{bmatrix}
                    1\\
                    1\\
                    -1
                  \end{bmatrix}\right)?
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li><p>Explain how this revisits the Unit 2 idea of nonunique coefficient vectors.</p></li>
          </ol>
          <p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U2-LO6, U6-LO5, U6-LO6 | C+R+M | Core]</c></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-u6-checkpoint-low-rank-update-storage">
        <title>Low-rank update storage</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let
            <me>
              W\in\mathbb R^{5000\times 3000},
              \qquad
              B\in\mathbb R^{5000\times 8},
              \qquad
              C\in\mathbb R^{8\times 3000}.
            </me>
            Define
            <me>W_{\text{new}}=W+BC.</me>
          </p>
          <ol marker="a">
            <li><p>What is the shape of <m>BC</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>What is the largest possible rank of <m>BC</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>How many numbers are needed to store <m>W</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>How many numbers are needed to store <m>B</m> and <m>C</m>?</p></li>
            <li><p>Why is <m>BC</m> called a low-rank update?</p></li>
            <li><p>Does this mean <m>W_{\text{new}}</m> must have low rank? Explain.</p></li>
          </ol>
          <p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U6-LO7 | C+M | Core]</c></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="u6-highlights">
    <title>Unit 6 highlights</title>
    <p><em>Big question.</em> What directions matter most in a constrained problem or matrix map?</p>
    <p>
      <em>Notation.</em> <m>\nabla f=\lambda\nabla g</m>, <m>\|\mathbf{x}\|=1</m>, <m>A^TA</m>, <m>A=U\Sigma V^T</m>, <m>\sigma_i</m>, <m>\mathbf{u}_i</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}_i</m>, <m>\operatorname{rank}(A)</m>, <m>\operatorname{row}(A)</m>, <m>\operatorname{col}(A)</m>, <m>\operatorname{null}(A)</m>, <m>\operatorname{null}(A^T)</m>,
      <me>A_k=U_k\Sigma_kV_k^T,</me>
      and
      <me>
        \frac{\sigma_1^2+\cdots+\sigma_k^2}
        {\sigma_1^2+\cdots+\sigma_r^2}.
      </me>
    </p>
    <p><em>Learning outcomes.</em> U6-LO1 through U6-LO7 ask you to compare constrained candidates, interpret parallel gradients, compute singular values and singular vectors, read and construct SVDs, identify fundamental subspaces, interpret stretch factors, and explain rank-<m>k</m> approximation or compression.</p>
    <p><em>Concepts.</em> Closed bounded region, boundary candidate, absolute extremum, constrained critical point, Lagrange multiplier, parallel gradients, quadratic form, maximum stretch, singular value, right singular vector, left singular vector, SVD, fundamental subspaces, rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction, energy retained, redundant feature, low-rank update.</p>
    <p>
      <em>Results.</em> A continuous function on a closed bounded region has absolute extrema. To find absolute extrema on a region, compare interior and boundary candidates. For a constraint <m>g(\mathbf{x})=k</m>, the Lagrange condition
      <me>\nabla f=\lambda\nabla g</me>
      means the objective gradient is parallel to the constraint gradient. For symmetric <m>B</m>, the extrema of
      <me>\mathbf{x}^TB\mathbf{x}</me>
      on the unit sphere occur at eigenvectors of <m>B</m>. Applying this to <m>B=A^TA</m> gives singular values and right singular vectors. The SVD
      <me>A=U\Sigma V^T</me>
      separates input directions, stretch factors, and output directions. Positive singular values identify transmitted directions; zero singular values identify forgotten directions. Truncated SVD keeps the largest singular directions.
    </p>
    <p><em>Toolbox skills.</em> U6-LO1 through U6-LO7 use candidate tables, boundary restrictions, Lagrange equations, <m>A^TA</m>, eigenvalues, eigenvectors, singular values, singular vectors, rank from SVD, fundamental subspaces, energy retained, NumPy SVD shapes, slicing such as <c>U[:, :k]</c> and <c>Vt[:k, :]</c>, and low-rank update storage counts.</p>
    <p><em>Main applications.</em> Constrained optimization on closed bounded sets, maximum stretch of a matrix map, dominant directions in data matrices, redundant-feature detection, SVD compression, rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction, energy retained, and model-matrix low-rank updates.</p>
    <p><em>Connections.</em> Unit 1 supplies vectors, matrix maps, matrix-vector products, shapes, and code-reading habits. Unit 2 supplies rank, null spaces, reachable outputs, forgotten directions, and redundant features. Unit 3 supplies gradients, level sets, tangent directions, closed sets, and bounded sets. Unit 4 supplies orthonormal bases and projection-like approximation language. Unit 5 supplies eigenvalues, eigenvectors, symmetric matrices, and quadratic forms. Unit 7 returns to best approximation, polynomial inner products, and low-rank structure.</p>
    <p><em>Study anchors.</em> U6-LO1: Absolute extrema on closed bounded regions. U6-LO2: Lagrange multipliers and parallel gradients. U6-LO3 and U6-LO6: Maximum stretch and singular values. U6-LO4 and U6-LO5: Singular value decomposition. U6-LO7: Low-rank approximation and compression. Code interpretation and exam-style checks: Applications and computation recap and linked notebook.</p>
    <p><em>Applications and computations readiness checklist.</em> Given a short Unit 6 calculation, code snippet, table, or diagram, I can decide whether boundary candidates are needed; set up Lagrange equations; interpret <m>\nabla f=\lambda\nabla g</m>; read <m>A^TA</m> as a maximum-stretch calculation; explain why singular values are square roots of eigenvalues of <m>A^TA</m>; read <c>U, s, Vt</c>; check the identity <m>A\mathbf{v}_i=\sigma_i\mathbf{u}_i</m>; find rank from singular values; identify row, column, and null-space directions from SVD; compute energy retained; explain what rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction keeps and discards; debug an incorrect SVD slice; and distinguish a low-rank update from a low-rank matrix.</p>
    <p><em>Common mistakes.</em> Ignoring boundary candidates; treating constrained critical points as final answers without comparing values; writing <m>\nabla f=\lambda\nabla f</m>; forgetting that <m>\nabla g</m> must be nonzero for the usual Lagrange condition; confusing <m>U</m>, <m>V</m>, and <m>V^T</m>; forgetting that singular values are nonnegative and usually sorted from largest to smallest; using <m>s</m> instead of <m>s^2</m> for energy retained; using <c>Vt[:, :k]</c> instead of <c>Vt[:k, :]</c>; treating a small numerical singular value as automatically exact zero; assuming a rank-<m>k</m> reconstruction is exact; or assuming <m>W+BC</m> must have low rank just because <m>BC</m> has low rank.</p>
  </section>
</chapter>
